The hierarchical solution
The trick is to extend the idea of a prior to multiple levels (Lambert 2018):

\begin{aligned}
\text{Likelihood:} \quad & x_{ij} \sim \text{Normal}(\mu_j,\ \sigma) && \text{(data within group } j)\\
\text{Group level:} \quad & \mu_j \sim \text{Normal}(\bar\mu,\ \bar\sigma) && \text{(groups drawn from a population)}\\
\text{Hyperprior:} \quad & \bar\mu \sim \text{Normal}(50,10),\ \ \bar\sigma \sim \text{Cauchy}^{+}(0,2.5) && \text{(population params inferred from data)}
\end{aligned}

The hyperparameters \bar\mu,\bar\sigma describe the population of groups and are learned from the data, not fixed (Lambert 2018). The structure assumes exchangeability: knowing nothing about the groups but their data, relabelling them wouldn’t change our beliefs — the justification for giving them a common prior (Lambert 2018).

When quant + qual genuinely beats either
Combining wins when the strands produce a more integrated and comprehensive answer than either could alone (Bryman 2016) — most often when:

the mechanism behind a measured effect is unknown (numbers locate it; words explain it);
you must build the instrument for a poorly-charted construct (qualitative work supplies the items);
a finding is important enough to need corroboration from an independent kind of evidence;
the population is hard to sample and one method bootstraps access to the other.

It does not help when the question is purely descriptive-quantitative or purely interpretive — then a second strand is cost without payoff.

Appendix · the full mathematics

Why the denominator cancels (the heart of MCMC). The Metropolis acceptance ratio for a proposed move \theta \to \theta' (with a symmetric proposal) is

r = \frac{p(\theta'\mid \text{data})}{p(\theta\mid \text{data})}
= \frac{\,p(\text{data}\mid\theta')\,p(\theta')\,/\,p(\text{data})\,}
       {\,p(\text{data}\mid\theta)\,p(\theta)\,/\,p(\text{data})\,}
= \frac{p(\text{data}\mid\theta')\,p(\theta')}{p(\text{data}\mid\theta)\,p(\theta)} .

The intractable p(\text{data}) appears identically in numerator and denominator and cancels — so the sampler needs only the unnormalised posterior (likelihood × prior). Accept if r \ge 1; otherwise accept with probability r (in practice compare \log r to \log u, u\sim\text{U}(0,1), for numerical stability — exactly the np.log(rng.random()) &lt; lp - lt test in the code).
Why the chain targets the posterior. Metropolis satisfies detailed balance with respect to the posterior \pi: \pi(\theta)\,T(\theta\to\theta') = \pi(\theta')\,T(\theta'\to\theta), which makes \pi the chain’s stationary distribution. An ergodic chain then converges to \pi regardless of start, so its long-run samples are posterior draws.
Monte Carlo error. For M (roughly independent) posterior draws, a posterior mean estimate has standard error \approx \sigma_{\text{post}}/\sqrt{M} — the same 1/\sqrt{M} law as everywhere else, so more samples buy more precision (slowly). Autocorrelation in the chain inflates this via the effective sample size M_{\text{eff}} &lt; M.
Equal-tailed vs HPD, formally. The equal-tailed interval is [\,q_{0.025},\,q_{0.975}\,] from the posterior quantile function. The 95% HPD is \{\theta : p(\theta\mid\text{data}) \ge c\} for the largest c with total mass 0.95 — the shortest such region, and the level-set that gives the pirate his disconnected digging zones when the posterior is multimodal.

The TWFE trap: Goodman–Bacon and negative weights
The old standard regresses the outcome on unit and time fixed effects plus a single treatment dummy, reporting one \beta_{\text{TWFE}} (Baker et al. 2025). Goodman-Bacon (2021) proved what that number actually is: a weighted average of every possible 2×2 DiD in the data (Baker et al. 2025), comparing:

treated vs never-treated (clean);
early-treated vs later-treated while the latter is still untreated (clean);
later-treated vs already-treated early adopters — the forbidden comparison (Baker et al. 2025).

The forbidden comparison is the poison. When effects are dynamic (they grow or fade), an already-treated unit’s outcome is still changing because of its own treatment — so using it as a “control” subtracts a moving target (Baker et al. 2025). This contamination attaches negative weights to some cohorts, and — the headline result — those negative weights can flip the sign: \beta_{\text{TWFE}} can come out negative even when every single cohort was helped by the treatment (Baker et al. 2025).

The setup
A cellular automaton has four ingredients (Sayama 2015):

a grid of cells (a line in 1-D, a lattice in 2-D);
a finite state per cell (often just on/off);
a neighbourhood (a cell’s immediate neighbours);
a local update rule mapping a cell’s neighbourhood to its next state.

The two non-negotiables: the rule is local (a cell sees only its neighbours, never the whole grid) and updates are parallel (every cell updates at once, from the same snapshot) (Sayama 2015). Everything interesting is emergent from those constraints.

Getting and setting components
Accessor functions pull a piece out of a date-time: year(), month(), mday() (day of month), yday() (day of year), wday() (day of week), hour(). (Wickham et al. 2023) The same functions set components (year(d) &lt;- 2020), or use update() to change several at once. And rounding — floor_date(), round_date(), ceiling_date() — snaps a date to a unit, which is exactly what you need to count “flights per week” before plotting. (Wickham et al. 2023)
flights |&gt;
  mutate(dep = make_datetime(year, month, day, hour, minute)) |&gt;
  count(week = floor_date(dep, "week")) |&gt;     # bucket into weeks, then
  ggplot(aes(week, n)) + geom_line()           # plot the weekly series
